article.description: Sue Bird proved Friday night a 5-foot-8 point guard can dominate a game.
article.headline: Bird's first double-double fuels Storm's comeback
article.linkText: Bird soars for Storm as Rockers pay price
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Sue Bird proved Friday night a 5-foot-8 point
guard can dominate a game.

	   Bird had her first double-double as a pro with 16 points and 12
assists to lead the Seattle Storm to a 73-65 comeback victory over
the Cleveland Rockers.

	   Bird, the No. 1 overall pick in the WNBA draft, was 4-for-4 from
the field and had nine assists in the second half as Seattle (8-8)
overcame a 53-40 deficit to snap a four-game road losing streak.

	   "We found something that worked and kept going to it,'' Bird
said.

	   That was the pick-and-roll, which Bird ran perfectly with power
forward Lauren Jackson, who led Seattle with 19 points.

	   "We are a very offensive team with Sue and myself,'' Jackson
said. "We just did not find our rhythm until the second half.''

	   Penny Taylor scored 16 points to lead Cleveland (6-9), which was
outscored 18-2 over the final 5:30 and lost for the fourth time at
home after leading by double digits.

	   "We have find a way to close out games,'' Rockers guard
Merlakia Jones said. "I don't have an answer right now. I think it
is just not being focused. They had 15 offensive boards and
converted each time.''

	   Cleveland native Sameka Randall had a career-high 10 rebounds --
eight offensive -- for Seattle.

	   "Sameka was really, really huge,'' Storm coach Lin Dunn said.
"The other thing was our defensive intensity. We took it to
another level the last four or five minutes. We were relentless.''

	   Cleveland shot 1-for-6 with five turnovers over the final 5:30.

	   Taylor scored 11 points in the first 9:21 of the second half to
help Cleveland lead 53-40. She shot 5-for-5, then did not take
another shot until missing a 3-pointer with 12 seconds to play.

	   Jackson scored eight consecutive Seattle points and Bird hit
three 3-pointers as the Storm rallied. Seattle tied the score at 63
on a 15-footer by Jackson, assisted by Bird, with 3:12 left.

	   Center Ann Wauters countered with a 6-footer for Cleveland with
2:55 left, but failed to complete the three-point play when she
missed a free throw -- the Rockers' first miss in 12 shots from the
line.

	   Michelle Marciniak put Seattle ahead to stay at 67-65 with a
fastbreak layup, triggered by Bird, with 1:53 remaining.

	   "Sue makes you feel really comfortable,'' said Marciniak, who
played the point down the stretch -- moving Bird to shooting guard.
"I took a little pressure off her. Then look what she did.''

	   Rookie Deanna Jackson hit all five of her shots for 10
first-half points to help Cleveland to a 34-29 lead. The Rockers'
first-round draft pick entered the game averaging 1.9 points and
finished with a season-high 14 points.

	   It was supposed to be the first meeting between possibly the
best point guards to play for college power Connecticut.
Cleveland's Jennifer Rizzotti and Bird rank 1-2 on the program's
all-time assist list, and are the only players in school history
with 1,000 points and 500 assists. But Rizzotti went on the injured
list Tuesday with a sprained right ankle.

	   "We lacked a true point guard for a lot of the game,'' Rockers
coach Dan Hughes said. "We weren't getting into the offensive flow
that we need.''
